```go\
const (\
    _ int = iota\
    LOWEST\
    ASSIGN      // =\
    LOGICAL     // && ||\
    COMPARISON  // == != < >\
    SUM         // + -\
    PRODUCT     // * / %\
    PREFIX      // -x !x\
    CALL        // func()\
    INDEX       // array[]\
)\
```\
\
Higher numbers = higher precedence.\
\
---\
\
### How It Works Step-by-Step\
\
```go\
func (p *Parser) parseExpression(precedence int) Expression \{\
    prefix := p.prefixParseFns[p.curToken.Type]\
    if prefix == nil \{ ... error ... \}\
\
    leftExp := prefix()   // Parse the left side\
\
    // Keep consuming infix operators as long as they have higher precedence\
    for !p.peekTokenIs(lexer.SEMICOLON) && precedence < p.peekPrecedence() \{\
        infix := p.infixParseFns[p.peekToken.Type]\
        if infix == nil \{\
            return leftExp\
        \}\
        p.nextToken()\
        leftExp = infix(leftExp)   // Parse the right side with current precedence\
    \}\
\
    return leftExp\
\}\
```\
\
**Example walkthrough**: `2 + 3 * 4`\
\
1. Start with `parseExpression(LOWEST)`\
2. `2` \uc0\u8594  prefix parser \u8594  `IntegerLiteral(2)`\
3. Peek is `+` (precedence = SUM)\
   - SUM > LOWEST \uc0\u8594  call infix parser for `+`\
4. Infix `+` parser:\
   - Left = 2\
   - Advance to `3`\
   - Call `parseExpression(SUM)` for right side\
5. Inside right side: `3` \uc0\u8594  prefix \u8594  Integer(3)\
6. Peek is `*` (PRODUCT > SUM) \uc0\u8594  consume `*`\
   - Call infix `*` with left=3\
   - Parse right side with PRODUCT precedence \uc0\u8594  `4`\
7. Result: `+(2, *(3, 4))`\
\
This correctly respects operator precedence.\
\
---\
\
### Key Components in Your Code\
\
**Prefix Parsers** (unary / atoms):\
- `parseIdentifier`\
- `parseIntegerLiteral`\
- `parsePrefixExpression` (`-x`, `!x`)\
- `parseIfExpression`, `parseFunctionLiteral`, etc.\
\
**Infix Parsers** (binary):\
- `parseInfixExpression` (`+`, `-`, `*`, `==`, etc.)\
- `parseCallExpression` (`func()`)\
- `parseIndexExpression` (`arr[0]`)\
\
**Registration**:\
```go\
p.registerPrefix(lexer.MINUS, p.parsePrefixExpression)\
p.registerInfix(lexer.PLUS, p.parseInfixExpression)\
```\
\
---\
\
### Advantages of Pratt Parser\
\
| Aspect                    | Recursive Descent          | Pratt Parser                  |\
|--------------------------|----------------------------|-------------------------------|\
| Expression complexity    | Hard (many rules)          | Easy (precedence table)       |\
| Operator precedence      | Manual handling            | Automatic                     |\
| Extensibility            | Painful                    | Just add token + parse fn     |\
| Left/right associativity | Tricky                     | Natural via precedence check  |\
| Code size for expressions| Large                      | Compact                       |\
\
---\
\
### Real Example from Navescript\
\
When parsing:\
```navescript\
let result = a + b * c == d\
```\
\
The parser builds the AST with correct grouping:\
```go\
LetStatement \{\
    Name: "result",\
    Value: Infix("==", \
        Infix("+", a, Infix("*", b, c)),\
        d\
    )\
\}\
```\
